😎😎😎 Vertical take-off in su-47 RC 😱😱😱😱👏👏👏👏👏👏👏👏👏👏👏
 HISTORY
Sukhoi Su-47 Berkut:
"The inverted arrow in the Russian style".

The concept of the inverted-swept wing, of interest in the field of low-speed flight control, dates back to the German four-engine Junkers Ju 287 V-1 bomber. In 1984, the Grumman X-29A experimental aircraft flew in the United States, the inverted boom requiring the use, at high speeds, of composite materials to ensure the desired rigidity of the wing. The Sukhoi Su-47 program began during the Cold War to counter the F-22 Raptor, a very ambitious program that scared the Soviets.

On September 25, 1997, Sukhoi flew its Su-47 Berkut (Royal Eagle) prototype, a Su-35-class fighter powered by two 12,500 kgp Saturn/Lyulka AL-31F engines. The aircraft has a canard plan, an inverted swept wing and a horizontal swept tail. Its flight controls are electric.

This inverted-sweep formula would allow it to have an unequalled manoeuvrability at all speeds: subsonic and supersonic. This manoeuvrability will be further increased with mobile vectorial nozzles which are to be added soon. The volume of the fuselage is designed to accommodate side bays for internal missile carriage.

The Su-47's weapon system would undoubtedly have been the most revolutionary point. It would have been articulated around the brand new N0014 active antenna multi-target radar made by Phazotron and Leninetz. This radar would have ensured a coverage of 360° what it would have allowed him to fire missiles towards the back! Another novelty, antennas derived from the Epaulet system were used to create a kind of jamming ball around the plane.

In its large cockpit, the pilot has a very clear view to the rear where only the tail fins are visible, set with a slight dihedral. In addition to the surprising speed of 2200 km/h, the Su-47 would show, according to its manufacturer, a good stealth‼️✈️ 🎥: @rp__rc

node.text:
Our home planet compared to the closest star, the mighty Sun!
🌟 ‼️✈️ 🎥: @bosplanet 

This gigantic plasma ball holds 99.8% of the solar system's mass and is roughly 109 times the diameter of the Earth — about one million Earths could fit inside the sun.

It may be the biggest thing in this neighborhood, but the #sun is just average compared to other stars. Betelgeuse, a red giant, is about 700 times bigger than the sun and about 14,000 times brighter.

For us, that average ball of life-giving light is everything, and the main reason we exist at all. Go outside and spend some time with it.

Peace out,
#bosplanet

🇲🇽 Mi-17 crashed in Mexico

 In the state of Hidalgo, Mexico, an Mi-17 helicopter belonging to the Mexican Navy crashed.

 The helicopter carried a group of officials, including the secretary of the government of Veracruz, who visited cities affected by the recent Hurricane Grace.

 It is reported that some of the passengers as a result of the helicopter crash received injuries of varying severity.  Fortunately, there were no fatalities in the incident‼️✈️ 🎥: Aircraft Studies LinkedIn
